e cusps: right coronary, left coronary and non-coronary"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aortic valve normally has \u003Cstrong\u003Ethree cusps: right coronary, left coronary and non-coronary\u003C/strong\u003E. These cusps are named based on their relationship to the coronary arteries, which arise from the sinuses of Valsalva just above the right and left coronary cusps. The non-coronary cusp does not have an associated coronary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach cusp attaches to the fibrous skeleton of the heart at the aortic root in a semilunar (half-moon) shape. When the cusps close during diastole, they meet in the centre of the valve orifice to prevent retrograde blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The aortic valve has three semilunar cusps: right coronary, left coronary, and non-coronary.","The aortic valve cusps attach to the fibrous skeleton of the heart at the aortic root in a semilunar (half-moon) shape.","The coronary arteries arise from the sinuses of Valsalva above the right and left coronary cusps."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18497"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T08:47:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T08:48:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11226"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":n